description: From Anglo-Norman, from Old French prince, from Latin prīnceps (“first head”), from prīmus (“first”) + capiō (“seize, take”). Doublet of princeps. Displaced native Old English æþeling.

entries.meaning: (now archaic or historical) A (male) ruler, a sovereign; a king, monarch. [from 13th c.]
examples: By his last years Erasmus realized that princes like Henry VIII and François I had deceived him in their elaborate negotiations for universal peace, but his belief in the potential of princely power for good remained undimmed.
Queen Elizabeth, a prince admirable above her sex.

entries.meaning: Someone who is preeminent in their field; a great person. [from 13th c.]
examples: He is a prince among men.

entries.meaning: The (male) ruler or head of a principality. [from 14th c.]
examples: He is the prince who never grew up – a one-time playboy and son of the Hollywood star Grace Kelly and Prince Rainier of Monaco.

entries.meaning: A male member of a royal family other than the ruler; especially (in the United Kingdom) the son or grandson of the monarch. [from 14th c.]
A non-royal high title of nobility, especially in France and the Holy Roman Empire.
examples: Prince Louis de Broglie won the 1929 Nobel Prize in Physics.

entries.meaning: A type of court card used in tarot cards, the equivalent of the jack.
Any of various nymphalid butterflies of the genus Rohana.
